revision.text:
{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}

[[File:UEFA.svg|thumb|350px|alt=A map of the world. The blue area, marked "UEFA", covers continental Europe, the British Isles, Iceland, and parts of Northern Asia and the Middle East.|{{legend|#4682b4|[[UEFA]] countries on this map of the world's six football confederations}}]]

The [[Union of European Football Associations]] (UEFA) is the administrative and controlling body for European [[association football|football]]. It consists of 55 member associations, each of which is responsible for governing football in their respective countries.<ref name=members>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7737736.stm|title=Big four to feel wind of European change|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=18 July 2010|date=8 December 2008|first=David|last=Ornstein}}</ref>

All widely recognised [[sovereign state]]s located entirely within Europe are members, with the exceptions of the United Kingdom, Monaco and Vatican City. Eight states partially or entirely outside Europe are also members: Armenia, Azerbaijan, Russia, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Israel, Cyprus and Turkey.<ref name=members/> The United Kingdom is divided into the four separate football associations of England, Northern Ireland, Scotland, and Wales; each association has a separate UEFA membership. The [[Faroe Islands]], an autonomous country of the Kingdom of Denmark, also has its own football association which is a member of UEFA.<ref name=members/> The football association of [[Gibraltar]], a [[British Overseas Territory]], was approved as a member by UEFA in 2013.<ref name=gibraltar>{{cite web|url= http://www.uefa.com/uefa/mediaservices/mediareleases/newsid=1956149.html|title= Gibraltar named 54th member of UEFA|date=24 May 2013|work=UEFA|accessdate=18 June 2013 }}</ref> [[Kosovo]] was approved as a member in 2016, even though it [[Political status of Kosovo|is claimed by Serbia]] and [[International recognition of Kosovo|is not recognised by several other UEFA member states]].

Each UEFA member has its own football [[league system]], except Liechtenstein.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=lie/profile/index.html|title=Liechtenstein making strides|publisher=[[UEFA]]|accessdate=19 July 2010|date=21 February 2010}}</ref> Clubs playing in each top-level league compete for the title as the country's club champions. Clubs also compete in the league and national cup competitions for places in the following season's UEFA club competitions, the [[UEFA Champions League]] and [[UEFA Europa League]]. Due to [[promotion and relegation]], the clubs playing in the top-level league are different every season, except in San Marino where there is only one level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=smr/profile/index.html|title=Solid foundations bolster San Marino|publisher=[[UEFA]]|accessdate=19 July 2010|date=21 February 2010}}</ref>

Some clubs play in a national football league [[List of association football clubs playing in the league of another country|other than their own country's]]. Where this is the case the club is noted as such.

{{horizontal TOC|nonum=yes}}

==UEFA coefficients==
{{main article|UEFA coefficient#League coefficient}}

The UEFA league coefficients, also known as the UEFA rankings, are used to rank the leagues of Europe, and thus determine the number of clubs from a league that will participate in UEFA Champions League and UEFA Europa League. A country's ranking determines the number of teams competing in the season after the next; the 2009 rankings determined qualification for European competitions in the 2010–11 season.<ref name=regulations>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/Regulations/competitions/Regulations/01/48/42/49/1484249_DOWNLOAD.pdf|title=Regulations of the UEFA Champions League 2010/11|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=16 August 2010|pages=41–48}}</ref>

A country's ranking is calculated based on the results of its clubs in UEFA competitions over the past five seasons. Two points are awarded for each win by a club, and one for a draw. If a game goes to extra time, the result at the end of time is used to calculate ranking points; if the match goes to a penalty shootout, it is considered to be a draw for the purposes of the coefficient system. The number of points awarded to a country's clubs are added together, and then divided by the number of clubs that participated in European competitions that season. This number is then rounded to three decimal places; two and two-thirds would become 2.667.<ref name=regulations/>

For the league coefficient the season's league coefficients for the last five seasons must be added up. In the preliminary rounds of both the Champions League and Europa League, the awarded points are halved. Bonus points for certain achievements are added to the number of points scored in a season. Bonus points are allocated for:

*Qualifying for the Champions League group phase. (4 bonus points)
*Reaching the second round of the Champions League. (5 bonus points)
*Reaching the quarter, semi and final of both Champions League and Europa League. (1 bonus point)<ref name=regulations/>

== Albania ==
{{main article|List of football clubs in Albania}}
* Football association: [[Football Association of Albania]]
* Top-level league: [[Albanian Superliga]] ({{lang-al|Kategoria superiore}})
* UEFA ranking: 34th<ref name=coefficient2018>2018 rankings are used; these determine qualification for European competitions in the 2018–19 season. {{cite web|url=https://kassiesa.home.xs4all.nl/bert/uefa/data/method5/crank2018.html|title=UEFA Country Ranking 2018|first=Bert|last=Kassies|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>
* Soccerway profile: [https://int.soccerway.com/national/albania/super-league here]

The top division of Albanian football was formed in 1930, and the inaugural title was won by SK Tirana (now known as KF Tirana). Tirana are the most successful team in the league's history, having won the competition on 24 occasions, followed by KS Dinamo Tirana (now playing in the [[Albanian First Division|second division]]) with 18 championships, and [[Partizani Tirana]] with 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/albachamp.html|title=Albania: List of champions|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|first=Eric|last=Boesenberg|date=19 May 2016 |accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref> The league became affiliated with UEFA in 1954.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=alb/index.html|title=Member associations: Albania|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> Since the [[2014–15 Albanian Superliga|2014–15 season]], 10 teams compete in the division. The teams finishing in the bottom two places are relegated to the [[Albanian First Division]] and are replaced by the champions of each of that league's two groups.

