==Bosnia and Herzegovina==
{{main article|List of football clubs in Bosnia and Herzegovina}}
* Country: Bosnia and Herzegovina
* Football association: [[Football Association of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]
* Top-level league: [[Premier League of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] ({{lang-bs|Premijer liga Bosne i Hercegovine}})
* UEFA ranking: 40th<ref name=coefficient2018/>
* Soccerway profile: [https://int.soccerway.com/national/bosnia-herzegovina/ here]

Prior to gaining independence from [[Yugoslavia]], clubs from Bosnia and Herzegovina were eligible to compete in the [[Yugoslav First League]], which they won three times. The country gained independence in 1992, and its Football Association gained UEFA membership in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=bih/index.html|title=Member associations: Bosnia-Herzegovina|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=16 August 2010}}</ref> Due to political tensions between [[Bosniaks]], [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Serbs]] and [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Croats]], the country did not have a single national top division until the 2002–03 season, but rather two or three. Since then, [[HŠK Zrinjski Mostar|Zrinjski]] have won five titles, [[FK Željezničar Sarajevo|Željezničar]] have won three, [[FK Sarajevo|Sarajevo]] and [[NK Široki Brijeg|Široki Brijeg]] have each won twice, and three other teams have won it once each.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bihchamp.html |title=Bosnia-Herzegovina: List of champions |first1=Igor |last1=Kramarsić |first2=Zoran |last2=Stojaković |date=24 August 2017 |accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref>

Since the 2016–17 season, the Premier League has consisted of 12 clubs, reduced from 16 in previous seasons. The 2016–17 season was the first for a two-stage season. In the first stage, each team plays all others home and away, after which the league splits into two six-team groups that also play home and away. The top six teams play for the championship and European qualifying places; the bottom six play to avoid relegation. At the end of the second stage, the bottom two clubs of the relegation group drop to either the [[First League of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] or the [[First League of the Republika Srpska]].<ref name="Bosnia">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bih2017.html |title=Bosnia-Hercegovina 2016/17 | publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |first1=Karel |last1=Stokkermans |date=6 October 2016 |accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref>

