==Croatia==
{{main article|List of football clubs in Croatia}}
* Country: Croatia
* Football association: [[Croatian Football Federation]]
* Top-level league: [[Croatian First Football League]] ({{lang-hr|Prva hrvatska nogometna liga}})
* UEFA ranking: 16th<ref name=coefficient2018/>
* Soccerway profile: [https://int.soccerway.com/national/croatia/ here]

National Croatian leagues were organised in 1914 and during the Second World War, but during peacetime Croatia's biggest clubs competed in the [[Yugoslav First League]]. After Croatia declared independence from [[Yugoslavia]] in 1991, a national football league was formed in 1992, and the Croatian Football Federation gained UEFA membership in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=cro/index.html|title=Member associations: Croatia|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=17 August 2010}}</ref> Since its formation, the Croatian First League has been dominated by NK Dinamo Zagreb and HNK Hajduk Split; as of the end of the 2015–16 season, one of these teams has won the title in all but one of the league's 25 seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesk/kroachamp.html|title=Croatia: List of champions|author1=Puric, Bojan |author2=Herceg, Boris |author3=Kramarsic, Igor  |lastauthoramp=yes|date=6 May 2016|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> Since the 2013–14 season, the First League has consisted of 10 teams. At the end of the season, the 10th-placed team is relegated directly to [[Croatian Second Football League|the second division]], while the 9th-placed team enters a relegation play-off.

