==England==
{{main article|List of football clubs in England}}
* Country: England
* Football association: [[The Football Association]]
* Top-level league: [[Premier League]]
* UEFA ranking: 2nd<ref name=coefficient2018/>
* Soccerway profile: [https://int.soccerway.com/national/england/ here]

Founded in 1888, the [[English Football League|Football League]] was the world's first national football league.<ref name=footballleague>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/page/History/HistoryDetail/0,,10794~1357277,00.html |publisher=The Football League |title=History of the Football League |date=16 June 2010 |accessdate=11 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090209043226/http://www.football-league.co.uk/page/History/HistoryDetail/0%2C%2C10794~1357277%2C00.html |archivedate=9 February 2009 |df= }}</ref> The inaugural competition was won by [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]], who remained unbeaten throughout the entire season. It was the top level football league in England from its foundation until [[1992–93 FA Premier League|1992]], when the 22 clubs comprising the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] resigned from the Football League to form the new FA Premier League.<ref name=footballleague/> As of the [[2017–18 Premier League|2017–18 season]] the Premier League comprises 20 clubs;<ref name=premhistory>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/History/0,,12306,00.html |title=A History of The Premier League |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=11 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111118121453/http://www.premierleague.com/page/History/0%2C%2C12306%2C00.html |archivedate=18 November 2011 |df= }}</ref> each team plays every other team twice, with the bottom 3 clubs at the end of the season relegated to the [[EFL Championship]]. The [[List of English football champions#Total titles won|most successful domestic club]] is [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], who have won the league 20 times, while the most successful English club in Europe is [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool FC]], who have won 5 [[UEFA Champions League|European Cups]], 3 [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cups]] and 3 [[UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cups]], more than any other English team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engchamp.html |title=England – List of champions |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |last=Ross |first=James M. |date=14 May 2010 |accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref>

''Clubs and locations as of [[2018–19 Premier League|2018–19 season]]'':
{{location map+ |England |width=440 |float=right |caption=Locations of the 2018–19 Premier League teams |places=
