==Estonia==
{{main article|List of football clubs in Estonia}}
* Country: Estonia
* Football association: [[Estonian Football Association]]
* Top-level league: [[Meistriliiga|Estonian Premier Division]] ({{lang-et|Meistriliiga}})
* UEFA ranking: 42nd<ref name=coefficient2018/>
* Soccerway profile: [https://int.soccerway.com/national/estonia/ here]

An independent Estonian league took place between 1921 and 1940. However, after the Second World War it became part of the Soviet Union, and became a regional system. Estonia regained independence after the dissolution of the [[USSR]], organising the first national championship in 52 years in 1992, the same year that the Estonian Football Association joined UEFA.<ref name=Estoniachamps>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/estchamp.html|title=Estonia: List of champions|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=17 November 2016|date=21 November 2016|first=Indrek|last=Petersoo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=est/index.html|title=Member associations: Estonia|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=31 August 2010}}</ref> FC Flora Tallinn is the most successful team in the modern era, with 10 league titles as of the end of the [[2016 Meistriliiga|2016 season]].<ref name=Estoniachamps/> Since [[2005 Meistriliiga|2005]], the Premier Division has consisted of 10 teams, which play one another four times. At the end of the season the bottom team is relegated to the [[Esiliiga|second level of Estonian football]], while the ninth-placed team enters into a relegation playoff.<ref name="Estonia">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/est2016.html|title=Estonia 2016|publisher = RSSSF|accessdate=17 May 2016|date=14 April 2016|first=Karel|last=Stokkermans}}</ref>

