==Faroe Islands==
{{main article|List of football clubs in Faroe Islands}}
* Country: Faroe Islands
* Football association: [[Faroe Islands Football Association]]
* Top-level league: [[Faroe Islands Premier League]] ({{lang-fo|Effodeildin}})
* UEFA ranking: 51st<ref name=coefficient2018/>
* Soccerway profile: [https://int.soccerway.com/national/faroe-islands/ here]

The Faroe Islands are a constituent country of the Kingdom of Denmark, which also comprises Greenland and Denmark itself. The league was formed in 1942, and has been contested annually since, with the exception of 1944 due to a lack of available balls.<ref name=faroelist>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesf/farchamp.html|title=Faroe Islands: List of champions|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=30 May 2016|first1=Gerd|last1=Heuser|first2=Hans|last2=Schöggl}}</ref> The Faroe Islands gained UEFA recognition in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=fro/index.html|title=Member associations: Faroe Islands|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=2 September 2010}}</ref> The most successful teams are Havnar Bóltfelag and KÍ Klaksvík, with 22 and 17 Premier League titles respectively as of the most recently completed 2016 season. Since the 1988 season, the Premier League has consisted of 10 teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesf/farplall.html |title=Faroe Islands - Final Placings (since 1979) |first=Markus |last=Schaal |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=29 January 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> They play each other three times, with the bottom two teams relegated to the [[1. deild|First Division]].

