==Sweden==
{{main article|List of football clubs in Sweden}}
* Country: Sweden
* Football association: [[Swedish Football Association]]
* Top-level league: [[Allsvenskan]] (''The All-Swedish'')
* UEFA ranking: 22nd<ref name=coefficient2018/>
* Soccerway profile: [https://int.soccerway.com/national/sweden/ here]

A Swedish championship was first organised in 1896, and the champions were decided by a knockout cup format until 1925, when Allsvenskan was formed.<ref name=swedenchamp>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwedchamp.html |title=Sweden: List of champions |first=Kent |last=Hedlundh |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |date=22 March 2018 |accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> Sweden was one of the founding members of UEFA in 1954.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=swe/index.html|title=Member associations: Sweden|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=6 September 2010}}</ref> As of the most recently completed [[2017 Allsvenskan|2017 season]], [[Malmö FF]] have won the most national titles with 20, followed by [[IFK Göteborg]] with 18 and [[IFK Norrköping]] with 13. Malmö also have the most league titles, with 23 to 13 for both IFK Götebörg and IFK Norrköping. Since [[2008 Allsvenskan|2008]],<ref name=sweden07>{{cite web|url=http://rsssf.com/tablesz/zwed07.html |title=Sweden 2007 |first=Clas |last=Glenning |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |date=28 March 2008 |accessdate=10 June 2014 |quote=NB: 1 club relegated, 3 promoted as Allsvenskan is extended to 16 clubs 2008.}}</ref> Allsvenskan has featured 16 teams. They each play one another home and away, for a total of 30 games. The bottom two teams are relegated to the [[Superettan]] (''The Super One''), and the 14th-placed Allsvenskan team enters into a relegation playoff with the 3rd-placed Superettan team to decide which will play in Allsvenskan for the following season.<ref name=sweden13>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwed13.html |title=Sweden 2013 |first=Karel |last=Stokkermans |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |date=3 April 2014 |accessdate=10 June 2014 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

''Clubs and locations as of [[2018 Allsvenskan|2018 season]]:''
