==Turkey==
{{main article|List of football clubs in Turkey}}
* Country: Turkey
* Football association: [[Turkish Football Federation]]
* Top-level league: [[Süper Lig]] (English: Super League)
* UEFA ranking: 10th<ref name=coefficient2018/>
* Soccerway profile: [https://int.soccerway.com/national/turkey/ here]

Turkish football operated on a regional basis until the 1950s. A national knockout tournament took place in 1957 and 1958, to decide European qualification. The Turkish Football Federation retrospectively recognised these tournaments as deciding the Turkish champions; both competitions were won by Beşiktaş J.K.<ref name=turchamp>{{cite web|url= http://www.rsssf.com/tablest/turkchamp.html |title=Turkey – List of Champions|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | first1=Baki |last1=Demirkiran |date=15 March 2018 |accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> A national league was formed in 1959, and has been held annually from then onwards.<ref name=turchamp/> Since the formation of a national league, the most successful teams are Galatasaray and Fenerbahçe, with 20 and 19 league titles respectively as of the most recently completed [[2016–17 Süper Lig|2016–17 season]]. Currently, 18 teams compete in the Süper Lig. Each team plays the other teams home and away, with the bottom three teams relegated to the [[TFF First League]] for the following season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablest/tur2016.html|title=Turkey 2009/10|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=26 May 2016|accessdate=29 May 2016|first=Erdinç|last=Sivritepe}}</ref>

