==Wales==
{{main article|List of football clubs in Wales}}
* Country: Wales
* Football association: [[Football Association of Wales]]
* Top-level league: [[Welsh Premier League]] ({{lang-cy|Cynghrair Cymru}})
* UEFA ranking: 50th<ref name=coefficient2018/>
* Soccerway profile: [https://int.soccerway.com/national/wales/ here]

Although Wales joined UEFA in 1954, Welsh football operated on a regional basis until 1992, with no national championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=wal/index.html|title=Member associations: Wales|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=3 September 2010}}</ref><ref name=waleslist/> Several Welsh clubs play not in the [[Welsh football league system]], but in the [[English football league system]]. Currently, one Welsh club, [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], competes in the [[Premier League]]. Another Welsh club, [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]], was relegated to the second level, the [[EFL Championship]], at the end of the 2017–18 season. Four other Welsh clubs participate lower down the English football league system: [[Newport County A.F.C.]], [[Wrexham F.C.]], [[Colwyn Bay F.C.]] and [[Merthyr Town F.C.]] Despite competing in Football Association competitions, the latter four are under the jurisdiction of the Football Association of Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_of_wales/8028480.stm|title=Welsh clubs 'could not leave' FAW|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 September 2010|date=1 May 2009}}</ref> Until 2011 Swansea City and Cardiff City had similar arrangements with the FAW but are now under the jurisdiction of The Football Association.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/may/06/fa-faw-cardiff-swansea Football Association breaks Welsh jurisdiction over Cardiff and Swansea]</ref> The most successful Welsh club since the formation of the Welsh Premier League is [[The New Saints F.C.|The New Saints]], with 12 league titles after having clinched their seventh straight league crown in 2017–18.<ref name=waleslist>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/walchamp.html|title=Wales: List of champions|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|first1=Hans|last1=Schöggl |first2=Karel|last2=Stokkermans  |date=29 March 2018 |accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> Since the [[2010–11 Welsh Premier League|2010–11 season]], the Welsh Premier League has featured 12 teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/wal2010.html |title=Wales 2009/10 |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |first1=Ian |last1=King |first2=Jan |last2=Schoenmakers |date=11 June 2015 |accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> Relegation to and promotion from lower regional leagues is in part dictated by whether or not clubs can obtain a Premier League licence; only clubs able to obtain a licence are eligible for promotion, and clubs which fail to obtain one are relegated regardless of their final league position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/wal2013.html|title=Wales 2012/13|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|first=Karel|last=Stokkermans|accessdate=29 August 2013|date=15 November 2013}}</ref>

